english:
  title: On the Royal Portrait of Yun Yuljung
  author: Hong Eon-bak
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A loyal and honest old scholar,
    With eyes too high, forever at odds with the world's desires.
    Why do you say nothing when you see me now?
    Your spirit is crisp and clear—your beard and brows have turned white.

    What the world calls "self" and "other" was never truly real;
    I know well this body is not meant to be preserved.
    Burning incense, sitting face to face, we pass the lamp together—
    Yet a Buddhist monk need not grasp the Way through robes alone.

    The generals on the Ling Yan pavilion achieved much glory,
    But never was their portrait brushed by the royal hand.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'lamp' (傳燈) references the Zen Buddhist transmission of enlightenment, suggesting the passing of spiritual truth beyond formal religious status.
  - key: ''
    value: The Ling Yan pavilion (凌烟閣) was a famous Tang Dynasty hall where portraits of distinguished generals and officials were displayed, symbolizing the highest worldly honor.
